     1â†’#### `--watcher`
     2â†’
     3â†’There are different backends used to determine when a file has changed.
cli/build.md
     1â†’# The build command
     2â†’
     3â†’The build command is used to render your book:
    16â†’#### Specify a directory
    17â†’
    18â†’The `build` command can take a directory as an argument to use as the book's
    19â†’root instead of the current working directory.
    25â†’#### `--open`
    26â†’
    27â†’When you use the `--open` (`-o`) flag, mdbook will open the rendered book in
    28â†’your default web browser after building it.
    30â†’#### `--dest-dir`
    31â†’
    32â†’The `--dest-dir` (`-d`) option allows you to change the output directory for the
    33â†’book. Relative paths are interpreted relative to the current directory. If
    34â†’not specified it will default to the value of the `build.build-dir` key in
    35â†’`book.toml`, or to `./book`.
cli/clean.md
     1â†’# The clean command
     2â†’
     3â†’The clean command is used to delete the generated book and any other build
     4â†’artifacts.
    10â†’#### Specify a directory
    11â†’
    12â†’The `clean` command can take a directory as an argument to use as the book's
    13â†’root instead of the current working directory.
    19â†’#### `--dest-dir`
    20â†’
    21â†’The `--dest-dir` (`-d`) option allows you to override the book's output
    22â†’directory, which will be deleted by this command. Relative paths are interpreted
    23â†’relative to the current directory. If not specified it will default to the
    24â†’value of the `build.build-dir` key in `book.toml`, or to `./book`.
cli/completions.md
     1â†’# The completions command
     2â†’
     3â†’The completions command is used to generate auto-completions for some common shells.
     4â†’This means when you type `mdbook` in your shell, you can then press your shell's auto-complete key (usually the Tab key) and it may display what the valid options are, or finish partial input.
cli/init.md
     1â†’# The init command
     2â†’
     3â†’There is some minimal boilerplate that is the same for every new book. It's for
     4â†’this purpose that mdBook includes an `init` command.
    32â†’#### Tip: Generate chapters from SUMMARY.md
    33â†’
    34â†’When a `SUMMARY.md` file already exists, the `init` command will first parse it
    35â†’and generate the missing files according to the paths used in the `SUMMARY.md`.
    36â†’This allows you to think and create the whole structure of your book and then
    37â†’let mdBook generate it for you.
    39â†’#### Specify a directory
    40â†’
    41â†’The `init` command can take a directory as an argument to use as the book's root
    42â†’instead of the current working directory.
    48â†’#### `--theme`
    49â†’
    50â†’When you use the `--theme` flag, the default theme will be copied into a
    51â†’directory called `theme` in your source directory so that you can modify it.
    56â†’#### `--title`
    57â†’
    58â†’Specify a title for the book. If not supplied, an interactive prompt will ask for 
    59â†’a title. 
    65â†’#### `--ignore`
    66â†’
    67â†’Create a `.gitignore` file configured to ignore the `book` directory created when [building] a book. 
    68â†’If not supplied, an interactive prompt will ask whether it should be created.
    80â†’#### `--force`
    81â†’
    82â†’Skip the prompts to create a `.gitignore` and for the title for the book.
cli/serve.md
     1â†’# The serve command
     2â†’
     3â†’The serve command is used to preview a book by serving it via HTTP at
     4â†’`localhost:3000` by default: 
    18â†’#### Specify a directory
    19â†’
    20â†’The `serve` command can take a directory as an argument to use as the book's
    21â†’root instead of the current working directory.
    27â†’### Server options
    28â†’
    29â†’The `serve` hostname defaults to `localhost`, and the port defaults to `3000`. Either option can be specified on the command line:
    35â†’#### `--open`
    36â†’
    37â†’When you use the `--open` (`-o`) flag, mdbook will open the book in your
    38â†’default web browser after starting the server.
    40â†’#### `--dest-dir`
    41â†’
    42â†’The `--dest-dir` (`-d`) option allows you to change the output directory for the
    43â†’book. Relative paths are interpreted relative to the current directory. If
    44â†’not specified it will default to the value of the `build.build-dir` key in
    45â†’`book.toml`, or to `./book`.
    49â†’#### Specify exclude patterns
    50â†’
    51â†’The `serve` command will not automatically trigger a build for files listed in
    52â†’the `.gitignore` file in the book root directory. The `.gitignore` file may
    53â†’contain file patterns described in the [gitignore
    54â†’documentation](https://git-scm.com/docs/gitignore). This can be useful for
    55â†’ignoring temporary files created by some editors.
cli/test.md
     1â†’# The test command
     2â†’
     3â†’When writing a book, you sometimes need to automate some tests. For example,
     4â†’[The Rust Programming Book](https://doc.rust-lang.org/stable/book/) uses a lot
     5â†’of code examples that could get outdated. Therefore it is very important for
     6â†’them to be able to automatically test these code examples.
    11â†’#### Disable tests on a code block
    12â†’
    13â†’rustdoc doesn't test code blocks which contain the `ignore` attribute:
    31â†’#### Specify a directory
    32â†’
    33â†’The `test` command can take a directory as an argument to use as the book's root
    34â†’instead of the current working directory.
    40â†’#### `--library-path`
    41â†’
    42â†’The `--library-path` (`-L`) option allows you to add directories to the library
    43â†’search path used by `rustdoc` when it builds and tests the examples. Multiple
    44â†’directories can be specified with multiple options (`-L foo -L bar`) or with a
    45â†’comma-delimited list (`-L foo,bar`). The path should point to the Cargo
    46â†’[build cache](https://doc.rust-lang.org/cargo/guide/build-cache.html) `deps` directory that
    47â†’contains the build output of your project. For example, if your Rust project's book is in a directory
    48â†’named `my-book`, the following command would include the crate's dependencies when running `test`:
    57â†’#### `--chapter`
    58â†’
    59â†’The `--chapter` (`-c`) option allows you to test a specific chapter of the
    60â†’book using the chapter name or the relative path to the chapter.
cli/watch.md
     1â†’# The watch command
     2â†’
     3â†’The `watch` command is useful when you want your book to be rendered on every
     4â†’file change. You could repeatedly issue `mdbook build` every time a file is
     5â†’changed. But using `mdbook watch` once will watch your files and will trigger a
     6â†’build automatically whenever you modify a file; this includes re-creating
     7â†’deleted files still mentioned in `SUMMARY.md`!
     9â†’#### Specify a directory
    10â†’
    11â†’The `watch` command can take a directory as an argument to use as the book's
    12â†’root instead of the current working directory.
    18â†’#### `--open`
    19â†’
    20â†’When you use the `--open` (`-o`) option, mdbook will open the rendered book in
    21â†’your default web browser.
    23â†’#### `--dest-dir`
    24â†’
    25â†’The `--dest-dir` (`-d`) option allows you to change the output directory for the
    26â†’book. Relative paths are interpreted relative to the current directory. If
    27â†’not specified it will default to the value of the `build.build-dir` key in
    28â†’`book.toml`, or to `./book`.
    32â†’#### Specify exclude patterns
    33â†’
    34â†’The `watch` command will not automatically trigger a build for files listed in
    35â†’the `.gitignore` file in the book root directory. The `.gitignore` file may
    36â†’contain file patterns described in the [gitignore
    37â†’documentation](https://git-scm.com/docs/gitignore). This can be useful for
    38â†’ignoring temporary files created by some editors.
continuous-integration.md
     1â†’# Running `mdbook` in continuous integration
     2â†’
     3â†’There are a variety of services such as [GitHub Actions] or [GitLab CI/CD] which can be used to test and deploy your book automatically.
    12â†’## Installing mdBook
    13â†’
    14â†’There are several different strategies for installing mdBook.
    15â†’The particular method depends on your needs and preferences.
    17â†’### Pre-compiled binaries
    18â†’
    19â†’Perhaps the easiest method is to use the pre-compiled binaries found on the [GitHub Releases page][releases].
    20â†’A simple approach would be to use the popular `curl` CLI tool to download the executable:
    39â†’### Building from source
    40â†’
    41â†’Building from source will require having Rust installed.
    42â†’Some services have Rust pre-installed, but if your service does not, you will need to add a step to install it.
    67â†’## Running tests
    68â†’
    69â†’You may want to run tests using [`mdbook test`] every time you push a change or create a pull request.
    70â†’This can be used to validate Rust code examples in the book.
    83â†’## Deploying
    84â†’
    85â†’You may want to automatically deploy your book.
    86â†’Some may want to do this every time a change is pushed, and others may want to only deploy when a specific release is tagged.
   100â†’### 404 handling
   101â†’
   102â†’mdBook automatically generates a 404 page to be used for broken links.
   103â†’The default output is a file named `404.html` at the root of the book.
   104â†’Some services like [GitHub Pages] will automatically use this page for broken links.
   105â†’For other services, you may want to consider configuring the web server to use this page as it will provide the reader navigation to get back to the book.
for_developers/README.md
     1â†’# For developers
     2â†’
     3â†’While `mdbook` is mainly used as a command line tool, you can also import the
     4â†’underlying libraries directly and use those to manage a book. It also has a fairly
     5â†’flexible plugin mechanism, allowing you to create your own custom tooling and
     6â†’consumers (often referred to as *backends*) if you need to do some analysis of
     7â†’the book or render it in a different format.
    17â†’## The build process
    18â†’
    19â†’The process of rendering a book project goes through several steps.
    30â†’## Using `mdbook` as a library
    31â†’
    32â†’The `mdbook` binary is just a wrapper around the underlying mdBook crates,
    33â†’exposing their functionality as a command-line program. If you want to
    34â†’programmatically drive mdBook, you can use the [`mdbook-driver`] crate.
    35â†’This can be used to add your own functionality or tweak the build process.
for_developers/backends.md
     1â†’# Alternative backends
     2â†’
     3â†’A "backend" is simply a program which `mdbook` will invoke during the book
     4â†’rendering process. This program is passed a JSON representation of the book and
     5â†’configuration information via `stdin`. Once the backend receives this
     6â†’information it is free to do whatever it wants.
    13â†’## Setting up
    14â†’
    15â†’This page will step you through creating your own alternative backend in the form
    16â†’of a simple word counting program. Although it will be written in Rust, there's
    17â†’no reason why it couldn't be accomplished using something like Python or Ruby.
    53â†’## Inspecting the book
    54â†’
    55â†’Now our backend has a copy of the book, lets count how many words are in each
    56â†’chapter!
    82â†’## Enabling the backend
    83â†’
    84â†’Now we've got the basics running, we want to actually use it. First, install the
    85â†’program.
   159â†’## Configuration
   160â†’
   161â†’Now imagine you don't want to count the number of words on a particular chapter
   162â†’(it might be generated text/code, etc). The canonical way to do this is via the
   163â†’usual `book.toml` configuration file by adding items to your `[output.foo]`
   164â†’table.
   219â†’## Output and signalling failure
   220â†’
   221â†’While it's nice to print word counts to the terminal when a book is built, it
   222â†’might also be a good idea to output them to a file somewhere. `mdbook` tells a
   223â†’backend where it should place any generated output via the `destination` field
   224â†’in [`RenderContext`].
   322â†’## Wrapping up
   323â†’
   324â†’Although contrived, hopefully this example was enough to show how you'd create
   325â†’an alternative backend for `mdbook`. If you feel it's missing something, don't
   326â†’hesitate to create an issue in the [issue tracker] so we can improve the user
   327â†’guide.
