format/configuration/README.md
     1â†’# Configuration
     2â†’
     3â†’This section details the configuration options available in the ***book.toml***:
     4â†’- **[General]** configuration including the `book`, `rust`, `build` sections
     5â†’- **[Preprocessor]** configuration for default and custom book preprocessors
     6â†’- **[Renderer]** configuration for the HTML, Markdown and custom renderers
     7â†’- **[Environment Variable]** configuration for overriding configuration options in your environment
format/configuration/environment-variables.md
     1â†’# Environment variables
     2â†’
     3â†’All configuration values can be overridden from the command line by setting the
     4â†’corresponding environment variable. Because many operating systems restrict
     5â†’environment variables to be alphanumeric characters or `_`, the configuration
     6â†’key needs to be formatted slightly differently to the normal `foo.bar.baz` form.
format/configuration/general.md
     1â†’# General configuration
     2â†’
     3â†’You can configure the parameters for your book in the ***book.toml*** file.
    31â†’## Supported configuration options
    32â†’
    33â†’It is important to note that **any** relative path specified in the
    34â†’configuration will always be taken relative from the root of the book where the
    35â†’configuration file is located.
    37â†’### General metadata
    38â†’
    39â†’This is general information about your book.
    64â†’### Rust options
    65â†’
    66â†’Options for the Rust language, relevant to running tests and playground
    67â†’integration.
    85â†’### Build options
    86â†’
    87â†’This controls the build process of your book.
format/configuration/preprocessors.md
     1â†’# Configuring Preprocessors
     2â†’
     3â†’Preprocessors are extensions that can modify the raw Markdown source before it gets sent to the renderer.
    26â†’## Custom preprocessor configuration
    27â†’
    28â†’Preprocessors can be added by including a `preprocessor` table in `book.toml` with the name of the preprocessor.
    29â†’For example, if you have a preprocessor called `mdbook-example`, then you can include it with:
    45â†’## Locking a preprocessor dependency to a renderer
    46â†’
    47â†’You can explicitly specify that a preprocessor should run for a renderer by
    48â†’binding the two together.
    55â†’## Provide your own command
    56â†’
    57â†’By default when you add a `[preprocessor.foo]` table to your `book.toml` file,
    58â†’`mdbook` will try to invoke the `mdbook-foo` executable. If you want to use a
    59â†’different program name or pass in command-line arguments, this behaviour can
    60â†’be overridden by adding a `command` field.
    67â†’### Optional preprocessors
    68â†’
    69â†’If you enable a preprocessor that isn't installed, the default behavior is to throw an error.
    70â†’This behavior can be changed by marking the preprocessor as optional:
    79â†’## Require a certain order
    80â†’
    81â†’The order in which preprocessors are run can be controlled with the `before` and `after` fields.
    82â†’For example, suppose you want your `linenos` preprocessor to process lines that may have been `{{#include}}`d; then you want it to run after the built-in `links` preprocessor, which you can require using either the `before` or `after` field:
format/configuration/renderers.md
     1â†’# Configuring Renderers
     2â†’
     3â†’Renderers (also called "backends") are responsible for creating the output of the book.
    20â†’## Output tables
    21â†’
    22â†’Backends can be added by including a `output` table in `book.toml` with the name of the backend.
    23â†’For example, if you have a backend called `mdbook-wordcount`, then you can include it with:
    59â†’### Custom backend commands
    60â†’
    61â†’By default when you add an `[output.foo]` table to your `book.toml` file,
    62â†’`mdbook` will try to invoke the `mdbook-foo` executable.
    63â†’If you want to use a different program name or pass in command-line arguments,
    64â†’this behaviour can be overridden by adding a `command` field.
    71â†’### Optional backends
    72â†’
    73â†’If you enable a backend that isn't installed, the default behavior is to throw an error.
    74â†’This behavior can be changed by marking the backend as optional:
    84â†’## HTML renderer options
    85â†’
    86â†’The HTML renderer has a variety of options detailed below.
    87â†’They should be specified in the `[output.html]` table of the `book.toml` file.
   176â†’### `[output.html.print]`
   177â†’
   178â†’The `[output.html.print]` table provides options for controlling the printable output.
   179â†’By default, mdBook will include an icon on the top right of the book (which looks like <i class="fas fa-print"></i>) that will print the book as a single page.
   191â†’### `[output.html.fold]`
   192â†’
   193â†’The `[output.html.fold]` table provides options for controlling folding of the chapter listing in the navigation sidebar.
   206â†’### `[output.html.playground]`
   207â†’
   208â†’The `[output.html.playground]` table provides options for controlling Rust sample code blocks, and their integration with the [Rust Playground].
   230â†’### `[output.html.code]`
   231â†’
   232â†’The `[output.html.code]` table provides options for controlling code blocks.
   244â†’### `[output.html.search]`
   245â†’
   246â†’The `[output.html.search]` table provides options for controlling the built-in text [search].
   247â†’mdBook must be compiled with the `search` feature enabled (on by default).
   286â†’#### `[output.html.search.chapter]`
   287â†’
   288â†’The [`output.html.search.chapter`] table provides the ability to modify search settings per chapter or directory. Each key is the path to the chapter source file or directory, and the value is a table of settings to apply to that path. This will merge recursively, with more specific paths taking precedence.
   300â†’### `[output.html.redirect]`
   301â†’
   302â†’The `[output.html.redirect]` table provides a way to add redirects.
   303â†’This is useful when you move, rename, or remove a page to ensure that links to the old URL will go to the new location.
   325â†’## Markdown renderer
   326â†’
   327â†’The Markdown renderer will run preprocessors and then output the resulting
   328â†’Markdown. This is mostly useful for debugging preprocessors, especially in
   329â†’conjunction with `mdbook test` to see the Markdown that `mdbook` is passing
   330â†’to `rustdoc`.
format/example.rs
     1â†’fn main() {
format/markdown.md
     1â†’# Markdown
     2â†’
     3â†’mdBook's [parser](https://github.com/raphlinus/pulldown-cmark) adheres to the [CommonMark](https://commonmark.org/) specification with some extensions described below.
     4â†’You can take a quick [tutorial](https://commonmark.org/help/tutorial/),
     5â†’or [try out](https://spec.commonmark.org/dingus/) CommonMark in real time. A complete Markdown overview is out of scope for 
     6â†’this documentation, but below is a high level overview of some of the basics. For a more in-depth experience, check out the
     7â†’[Markdown Guide](https://www.markdownguide.org).
     9â†’## Text and paragraphs
    10â†’
    11â†’Text is rendered relatively predictably: 
    25â†’## Headings
    26â†’
    27â†’Headings use the `#` marker and should be on a line by themselves. More `#` mean smaller headings:
    39â†’### A heading 
    40â†’
    41â†’Some text.
    43â†’#### A smaller heading 
    44â†’
    45â†’More text.
    47â†’## Lists
    48â†’
    49â†’Lists can be unordered or ordered. Ordered lists will order automatically:
    69â†’## Links
    70â†’
    71â†’Linking to a URL or local file is easy:
   108â†’## Images
   109â†’
   110â†’Including images is simply a matter of including a link to them, much like in the _Links_ section above. The following markdown
   111â†’includes the Rust logo SVG image found in the `images` directory at the same level as this file:
   127â†’## Extensions
   128â†’
   129â†’mdBook has several extensions beyond the standard CommonMark specification.
   131â†’### Strikethrough
   132â†’
   133â†’Text may be rendered with a horizontal line through the center by wrapping the
   134â†’text with one or two tilde characters on each side:
   146â†’### Footnotes
   147â†’
   148â†’A footnote generates a small numbered link in the text which when clicked
   149â†’takes the reader to the footnote text at the bottom of the item. The footnote
   150â†’label is written similarly to a link reference with a caret at the front. The
   151â†’footnote text is written like a link reference definition, with the text
   152â†’following the label. Example:
   171â†’### Tables
   172â†’
   173â†’Tables can be written using pipes and dashes to draw the rows and columns of
   174â†’the table. These will be translated to HTML table matching the shape. Example:
   191â†’### Task lists
   192â†’
   193â†’Task lists can be used as a checklist of items that have been completed.
   194â†’Example:
   208â†’### Smart punctuation
   209â†’
   210â†’Some ASCII punctuation sequences will be automatically turned into fancy Unicode
   211â†’characters:
   231â†’### Heading attributes
   232â†’
   233â†’Headings can have a custom HTML ID and classes. This lets you maintain the same ID even if you change the heading's text, it also lets you add multiple classes in the heading.
   244â†’### Definition lists
   245â†’
   246â†’Definition lists can be used for things like glossary entries. The term is listed on a line by itself, followed by one or more definitions. Each definition must begin with a `:` (after 0-2 spaces).
   279â†’### Admonitions
   280â†’
   281â†’An admonition is a special type of callout or notice block used to highlight important information. It is written as a blockquote with a special tag on the first line.
format/mathjax.md
     1â†’# MathJax support
     2â†’
     3â†’mdBook has optional support for math equations through
     4â†’[MathJax](https://www.mathjax.org/).
    24â†’### Inline equations
    25â†’Inline equations are delimited by `\\(` and `\\)`. So for example, to render the
    26â†’following inline equation \\( \int x dx = \frac{x^2}{2} + C \\) you would write
    27â†’the following:
    28â†’```
    29â†’\\( \int x dx = \frac{x^2}{2} + C \\)
    30â†’```
    32â†’### Block equations
    33â†’Block equations are delimited by `\\[` and `\\]`. To render the following
    34â†’equation
format/mdbook.md
     1â†’# mdBook-specific features
     2â†’
     3â†’## Hiding code lines
     4â†’
     5â†’There is a feature in mdBook that lets you hide code lines by prepending them with a specific prefix.
    74â†’## Rust playground
    75â†’
    76â†’Rust language code blocks will automatically get a play button (<i class="fas fa-play"></i>) which will execute the code and display the output just below the code block.
    77â†’This works by sending the code to the [Rust Playground].
   102â†’## Rust code block attributes
   103â†’
   104â†’Additional attributes can be included in Rust code blocks with comma, space, or tab-separated terms just after the language term. For example:
   133â†’## Including files
   134â†’
   135â†’With the following syntax, you can include files into your book:
   154â†’## Including portions of a file
   155â†’Often you only need a specific part of the file, e.g. relevant lines for an
   156â†’example. We support four different modes of partial includes:
   215â†’## Including a file but initially hiding all except specified lines
   216â†’
   217â†’The `rustdoc_include` helper is for including code from external Rust files that contain complete
   218â†’examples, but only initially showing particular lines specified with line numbers or anchors in the
   219â†’same way as with `include`.
   279â†’## Inserting runnable Rust files
   280â†’
   281â†’With the following syntax, you can insert runnable Rust files into your book:
   310â†’## Controlling page \<title\>
   311â†’
   312â†’A chapter can set a \<title\> that is different from its entry in the table of
   313â†’contents (sidebar) by including a `\{{#title ...}}` near the top of the page.
   319â†’## HTML classes provided by mdBook
   320â†’
   321â†’<img class="right" src="images/rust-logo-blk.svg" alt="The Rust logo">
   323â†’### `class="left"` and `"right"`
   324â†’
   325â†’These classes are provided by default, for inline HTML to float images.
   331â†’### `class="hidden"`
   332â†’
   333â†’HTML tags with class `hidden` will not be shown.
   341â†’## Font-Awesome icons
   342â†’
   343â†’mdBook includes a copy of version 6 of [Font Awesome Free's](https://fontawesome.com)
   344â†’MIT-licensed SVG files. It emulates the `<i>` syntax, but converts the results
   345â†’to inline SVG. Only the regular, solid, and brands icons are included; paid
   346â†’features like the light icons are not.
format/summary.md
     1â†’# SUMMARY.md
     2â†’
     3â†’The summary file is used by mdBook to know what chapters to include, in what
     4â†’order they should appear, what their hierarchy is and where the source files
     5â†’are. Without this file, there is no book.
    12â†’### Structure
    13â†’
    14â†’1. ***Title*** - While optional, it's common practice to begin with a title, generally <code
    15â†’   class="language-markdown"># Summary</code>. This is ignored by the parser however, and
    16â†’   can be omitted.
    17â†’   ```markdown
    18â†’   # Summary
    19â†’   ```
    93â†’### Example
    94â†’
    95â†’Below is the markdown source for the `SUMMARY.md` for this guide, with the resulting table
    96â†’of contents as rendered to the left.
